2026-03-03 09:37:05.0484 - DEBUG - graphrag.api.index - [{'id': '6f51438faffcaa01448c46a96fa1c90dab9623dbbb63bfbe4db8813ae84a41ee8e53b8feffc5dfb1d89d31877e9dcdfa3099861d54cd63636207b56528051cdb', 'document_id': '6f51438faffcaa01448c46a96fa1c90dab9623dbbb63bfbe4db8813ae84a41ee8e53b8feffc5dfb1d89d31877e9dcdfa3099861d54cd63636207b56528051cdb', 'text': "The Apollo Program was a NASA spaceflight program that ran from 1961 to 1972. It was designed to land humans on the Moon and bring them safely back to Earth. The program was conceived during the presidency of Dwight D. Eisenhower but was formally announced by President John F. Kennedy on May 25, 1961, during a special address to Congress. Kennedy declared the ambitious goal of landing a man on the Moon before the end of the decade.\n\nNASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, was responsible for managing the Apollo program. The agency worked closely with several major contractors. North American Aviation built the Command and Service Module, while Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation designed and manufactured the Lunar Module. The Saturn V rocket, the most powerful rocket ever built at the time, was developed under the direction of Wernher von Braun at the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama.\n\nThe program suffered a devastating setback on January 27, 1967, when a cabin fire during a launch rehearsal test for Apollo 1 killed astronauts Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger Chaffee at Cape Kennedy in Florida. The tragedy led to major design and engineering changes in the spacecraft and a twenty-month delay in crewed flights.\n\nApollo 7, launched on October 11, 1968, was the first crewed Apollo mission and successfully tested the Command Module in Earth orbit. Apollo 8, launched on December 21, 1968, became the first crewed spacecraft to leave low Earth orbit, reach the Moon, orbit it, and return safely. Astronauts Frank Borman, Jim Lovell, and William Anders became the first humans to see the far side of the Moon.\n\nThe culmination of the program came with Apollo 11 on July 20, 1969. Commander Neil Armstrong and Lunar Module Pilot Buzz Aldrin landed the Lunar Module Eagle on the Moon's Sea of Tranquility while Command Module Pilot Michael Collins orbited above. Armstrong became the first human to set foot on the lunar surface, followed by Aldrin approximately twenty minutes later.\n", 'n_tokens': 426}, {'id': '3549bb0ef19b0b45493f6fa077a298d7e498a7d47c352b0271adbeec33827b419c2ff5f00392c398d0f0b775f3c9c2a6be5c800bc8ccf4391c6ace06702a0595', 'document_id': '3549bb0ef19b0b45493f6fa077a298d7e498a7d47c352b0271adbeec33827b419c2ff5f00392c398d0f0b775f3c9c2a6be5c800bc8ccf4391c6ace06702a0595', 'text': 'Following the success of Apollo 11, NASA continued its lunar exploration with five more successful landing missions. Apollo 12, commanded by Pete Conrad with Alan Bean as Lunar Module Pilot and Richard Gordon as Command Module Pilot, launched on November 14, 1969. The mission demonstrated precision landing capability by touching down within walking distance of the Surveyor 3 probe that had landed on the Moon two years earlier.\n\nApollo 13 launched on April 11, 1970, with astronauts Jim Lovell, Jack Swigert, and Fred Haise. An oxygen tank explosion in the Service Module forced the crew to abandon the planned Moon landing and use the Lunar Module as a lifeboat. The mission became known as a successful failure due to the remarkable efforts of the crew and Mission Control in Houston, Texas, to bring the astronauts safely home.\n\nApollo 14, launched on January 31, 1971, saw astronaut Alan Shepard, the first American in space, walk on the Moon accompanied by Edgar Mitchell. Apollo 15, launched on July 26, 1971, was the first extended scientific expedition to the Moon. Commander David Scott and Lunar Module Pilot James Irwin spent three days on the lunar surface at the Hadley-Apennine region, using the first Lunar Roving Vehicle.\n\nApollo 16, launched on April 16, 1972, landed in the Descartes Highlands with astronauts John Young and Charles Duke conducting extensive geological surveys. The final mission, Apollo 17, launched on December 7, 1972. Commander Eugene Cernan and Lunar Module Pilot Harrison Schmitt, a trained geologist, spent over three days on the surface in the Taurus-Littrow valley. Cernan remains the last human to have walked on the Moon.\n\nIn total, twelve astronauts walked on the lunar surface during the Apollo program. The missions returned approximately 842 pounds of lunar samples and deployed numerous scientific instruments that continued transmitting data long after the astronauts departed.\n', 'n_tokens': 401}, {'id': '4f0f65796bccf7a95bdf2969da83af426406e1efb39fca53a62d5e4f5c48b7746a2e48a4045d6db39eb56b528a0b1424777d734d10e7606fef9133e399917ee8', 'document_id': '4f0f65796bccf7a95bdf2969da83af426406e1efb39fca53a62d5e4f5c48b7746a2e48a4045d6db39eb56b528a0b1424777d734d10e7606fef9133e399917ee8', 'text': "The legacy of the Apollo program extends far beyond the Moon landings themselves. The program demonstrated that international cooperation and competition could drive extraordinary achievements. The Space Race between the United States and the Soviet Union provided the political motivation for Apollo, but its scientific and cultural impact transcended Cold War rivalries.\n\nThe lunar samples returned by Apollo missions revolutionized our understanding of the Moon's origin and geology. Analysis at the Lunar Receiving Laboratory at the Manned Spacecraft Center in Houston confirmed the Giant Impact Hypothesis, which proposes that the Moon formed from debris created when a Mars-sized body called Theia collided with the early Earth approximately 4.5 billion years ago.\n\nApollo also transformed our view of Earth itself. The famous Earthrise photograph taken by William Anders during Apollo 8 and the Blue Marble photograph from Apollo 17 became iconic images that helped spark the environmental movement. Seeing Earth as a fragile, beautiful sphere floating in the darkness of space gave humanity a new perspective on the planet's vulnerability.\n\nThe Artemis program, announced by NASA in 2017, aims to return humans to the Moon by the mid-2020s. Building on Apollo's legacy, Artemis plans to establish a sustainable presence on and around the Moon using the Space Launch System rocket and the Orion spacecraft. The program involves international partners including the European Space Agency, the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency, and the Canadian Space Agency.\n\nSpaceX, founded by Elon Musk, has been contracted by NASA to develop the Human Landing System for Artemis using a modified version of the Starship vehicle. Blue Origin, founded by Jeff Bezos, is developing a separate lunar lander. These commercial partnerships represent a significant evolution from the Apollo era, when the government managed virtually all aspects of spaceflight development.\n\nThe Apollo astronauts became cultural icons. Neil Armstrong, known for his humility and reluctance to seek the spotlight, was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Richard Nixon. Buzz Aldrin became a prominent advocate for Mars exploration. Many Apollo astronauts reported profound psychological and philosophical changes from seeing Earth from space, an experience known as the Overview Effect.\n", 'n_tokens': 415}, {'id': '0135e7d6044f0c25f0540cc19bd2c633d1d84904cc3aac7dd288a2ff18d759d720c0b7df603e4204942667b4b99755ee88f5dc1fd48ba164867ea6915c287536', 'document_id': '0135e7d6044f0c25f0540cc19bd2c633d1d84904cc3aac7dd288a2ff18d759d720c0b7df603e4204942667b4b99755ee88f5dc1fd48ba164867ea6915c287536', 'text': 'The technological achievements of the Apollo program were extraordinary and required innovation across multiple engineering disciplines. The Saturn V rocket stood 363 feet tall and generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust at liftoff. It was developed at the Marshall Space Flight Center under the leadership of Wernher von Braun, a German-born rocket engineer who had previously developed the V-2 rocket during World War II.\n\nThe Command Module, built by North American Aviation in Downey, California, served as the crew quarters and flight control section for the entire mission. It was the only part of the spacecraft that returned to Earth. The Service Module, also built by North American Aviation, contained the propulsion system and most of the consumables such as oxygen, water, and electrical power.\n\nThe Lunar Module, manufactured by Grumman in Bethpage, New York, was a two-stage spacecraft designed exclusively for operations in the vacuum of space. Its descent stage included the engine for landing on the Moon and served as a launch platform for the ascent stage, which carried the crew back to lunar orbit to rendezvous with the Command Module.\n\nMission Control Center at the Manned Spacecraft Center in Houston, Texas, served as the nerve center for all Apollo missions. Flight Directors such as Gene Kranz, Chris Kraft, and Glynn Lunney coordinated thousands of engineers and controllers who monitored every aspect of the missions in real time.\n\nThe Apollo Guidance Computer, developed at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory under the direction of Charles Stark Draper, was a pioneering digital computer that used integrated circuits. Margaret Hamilton, who led the software engineering team at MIT, developed the onboard flight software that proved critical during the Apollo 11 landing when the computer successfully managed multiple program alarms.\n\nThe program also drove advances in materials science, telecommunications, life support systems, and project management. Many technologies developed for Apollo found applications in everyday life, from water purification systems to fireproof materials. The total cost of the Apollo program was approximately 25.4 billion dollars, equivalent to over 150 billion dollars in modern currency.\n', 'n_tokens': 411}]
