2026-03-03 09:37:07.0976 - DEBUG - graphrag.api.index - [{'id': '6f51438faffcaa01448c46a96fa1c90dab9623dbbb63bfbe4db8813ae84a41ee8e53b8feffc5dfb1d89d31877e9dcdfa3099861d54cd63636207b56528051cdb', 'human_readable_id': 0, 'text': "The Apollo Program was a NASA spaceflight program that ran from 1961 to 1972. It was designed to land humans on the Moon and bring them safely back to Earth. The program was conceived during the presidency of Dwight D. Eisenhower but was formally announced by President John F. Kennedy on May 25, 1961, during a special address to Congress. Kennedy declared the ambitious goal of landing a man on the Moon before the end of the decade.\n\nNASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, was responsible for managing the Apollo program. The agency worked closely with several major contractors. North American Aviation built the Command and Service Module, while Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation designed and manufactured the Lunar Module. The Saturn V rocket, the most powerful rocket ever built at the time, was developed under the direction of Wernher von Braun at the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama.\n\nThe program suffered a devastating setback on January 27, 1967, when a cabin fire during a launch rehearsal test for Apollo 1 killed astronauts Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger Chaffee at Cape Kennedy in Florida. The tragedy led to major design and engineering changes in the spacecraft and a twenty-month delay in crewed flights.\n\nApollo 7, launched on October 11, 1968, was the first crewed Apollo mission and successfully tested the Command Module in Earth orbit. Apollo 8, launched on December 21, 1968, became the first crewed spacecraft to leave low Earth orbit, reach the Moon, orbit it, and return safely. Astronauts Frank Borman, Jim Lovell, and William Anders became the first humans to see the far side of the Moon.\n\nThe culmination of the program came with Apollo 11 on July 20, 1969. Commander Neil Armstrong and Lunar Module Pilot Buzz Aldrin landed the Lunar Module Eagle on the Moon's Sea of Tranquility while Command Module Pilot Michael Collins orbited above. Armstrong became the first human to set foot on the lunar surface, followed by Aldrin approximately twenty minutes later.\n", 'n_tokens': 426, 'document_id': '6f51438faffcaa01448c46a96fa1c90dab9623dbbb63bfbe4db8813ae84a41ee8e53b8feffc5dfb1d89d31877e9dcdfa3099861d54cd63636207b56528051cdb', 'entity_ids': ['2e1ad435-c02d-4601-9916-3979af75b8cb', '63e22b25-909f-461e-8892-86f537976307', '9fef917d-9928-499b-80b2-f619699d85c3', '1cce2f15-17a7-4107-8833-2c490a49a693', '383d206e-5328-4531-9709-c173161eb12b', 'c298f192-6149-4a80-96d6-e1db5d8e7c03', 'b155f528-dfa9-46e0-8037-2c8df4773d8a', 'f9ef2cc8-fad2-4d8f-a929-a45b434f02d5', '7f6579a8-681e-49a2-82ca-cbfb3fc09b25', 'f3b467c2-ede6-4868-b8d3-b94beda91d57', '444762ba-62af-4d67-b5d5-312ae5e436fa', '280fa8cb-97e5-4a2f-8955-4e710cc92e97', '6915d4ab-a97d-457a-9fe1-2bef28962a0e', '43523f56-d53d-4b56-a72b-bb8d43578e03', '78c138bc-c67c-426a-934d-81f8de939163', '43cd4815-5caf-44d3-9735-86280499c2da', 'd3ccd8f6-fe86-4c59-b147-421805dff030', 'b4d7972b-028b-4fe7-a2b6-ca88fe3a112e', '13b164d7-dbab-4958-aab2-ac8088cef9b5', '7a2fc159-cfb2-4d01-a55f-5179dfb99f05', 'f09acdc4-f6d4-46b5-90af-74ae1abc30ba', 'cd85c9b4-0135-4865-ba8a-c7b07e007fca', '95a71420-15b8-4f82-9256-107e3a726ff4', '01938521-8883-423e-b92a-e7d7f2b20292', 'f409d954-1549-4e0c-9010-4b83a0abc983', '3f67da93-5857-4b16-9dd2-ef8da4883666', 'd5af0b1e-9dc5-4cf4-880d-e7eab1988782', '02959ad6-fb52-4d24-9fd2-53ba28239998', '3b6cf6d7-aaaa-48c5-a1c0-6239440b499d', 'ade2d442-f200-415c-be55-c0d671e99f30', '0064d61e-0f45-499a-9414-6efb02c76ae5', '80401a13-083a-4cd4-91bb-cbfc0f555d6f'], 'relationship_ids': ['a298f827-dbaa-40f9-8a3e-d58ea4c07fae', '6eb9a861-2e60-40e6-a703-c0b2ebef045c', '555ff3eb-f34b-4056-a21c-eecc81dbfe96', '4e981de8-66f9-4d54-8d72-cb730069e603', '4153cba8-4f53-4951-8edd-5fe6786d43f5', 'f94f986e-1004-4df9-9630-fa5d23c01086', '5e7cc544-d784-42df-b8f9-e584b740049d', '63f2f1f6-df15-4fbf-a05b-a8b5950ff6c3', '8c3ab3ec-be6b-4b65-a94d-ef725f5d8eb1', 'bf9abd94-71f2-4f41-8130-9dd8013f9c37', 'bb430080-c652-47ab-9a1f-f15445fbc8b9', '5ecc1bdb-2ff8-48b7-a971-2a96a635ca31', '38b6cbfa-203b-46cc-a330-95836fd323a2', '3933025e-5310-4388-ae46-c838976fda60', '3eea7ad9-5a3d-4601-96d1-45ade2cdaba2', 'a043bf02-d6fa-47de-b23b-6551acb07afc', '5c6f1dc7-7ecb-4475-a1b5-003de835a784', '50802cfe-ae34-49ac-9d50-f1ec2d8d1eae', '3f66aa97-2603-4251-b7e2-f6105c1733a3', 'cd5c926e-ad8d-4d9d-b389-6081883e6a02', '7cd4181b-f184-48e8-9484-614e2c6158e3', 'e2187f96-6cee-4c4b-a779-2741cc3a6e9f', 'e2ba8a91-271c-4aa9-9b9b-7c5f648f8ba6', '349a3981-0c5d-4f6c-a7dc-883d50bd949c', '9e4944f7-c649-49d1-9bf8-d5130bb47122', '75ada6ef-dc17-460d-942d-2dc37271110e', 'dcd5c275-9d0a-4f65-9721-4294adefc952', '65466150-4821-487b-96f0-e294f99c4713', '6d586635-01ce-42e1-b5db-4dc39259b496', '54f7698a-2bb5-4ecd-93bc-2ccef3a71fdc', '7a5cca4b-ec5b-40f5-9365-9413e94437be', '957fe310-2f71-4e31-8388-bbe6913b4abf', 'b636d77b-2cfe-47a6-ba1c-8424340064e7', '55023eac-2a1a-41ae-ba2f-c2b98ee83633', 'ee65fe09-1c58-4754-bac6-8da07b3f7550', '287c72b5-9ed1-401a-93d6-9188c4debc4a', 'e115a84d-1c2b-433d-a911-d7cdf5753a6d', '48dcf7b3-38d1-486d-b435-b901fb150686', 'c7588d6c-8cd1-4d35-ae49-c26769caade8', '76ced280-df50-47f4-97e5-0a84b8db21af', '3f37d257-1d94-475f-b08a-5470fb3b26bd'], 'covariate_ids': []}, {'id': '3549bb0ef19b0b45493f6fa077a298d7e498a7d47c352b0271adbeec33827b419c2ff5f00392c398d0f0b775f3c9c2a6be5c800bc8ccf4391c6ace06702a0595', 'human_readable_id': 1, 'text': 'Following the success of Apollo 11, NASA continued its lunar exploration with five more successful landing missions. Apollo 12, commanded by Pete Conrad with Alan Bean as Lunar Module Pilot and Richard Gordon as Command Module Pilot, launched on November 14, 1969. The mission demonstrated precision landing capability by touching down within walking distance of the Surveyor 3 probe that had landed on the Moon two years earlier.\n\nApollo 13 launched on April 11, 1970, with astronauts Jim Lovell, Jack Swigert, and Fred Haise. An oxygen tank explosion in the Service Module forced the crew to abandon the planned Moon landing and use the Lunar Module as a lifeboat. The mission became known as a successful failure due to the remarkable efforts of the crew and Mission Control in Houston, Texas, to bring the astronauts safely home.\n\nApollo 14, launched on January 31, 1971, saw astronaut Alan Shepard, the first American in space, walk on the Moon accompanied by Edgar Mitchell. Apollo 15, launched on July 26, 1971, was the first extended scientific expedition to the Moon. Commander David Scott and Lunar Module Pilot James Irwin spent three days on the lunar surface at the Hadley-Apennine region, using the first Lunar Roving Vehicle.\n\nApollo 16, launched on April 16, 1972, landed in the Descartes Highlands with astronauts John Young and Charles Duke conducting extensive geological surveys. The final mission, Apollo 17, launched on December 7, 1972. Commander Eugene Cernan and Lunar Module Pilot Harrison Schmitt, a trained geologist, spent over three days on the surface in the Taurus-Littrow valley. Cernan remains the last human to have walked on the Moon.\n\nIn total, twelve astronauts walked on the lunar surface during the Apollo program. The missions returned approximately 842 pounds of lunar samples and deployed numerous scientific instruments that continued transmitting data long after the astronauts departed.\n', 'n_tokens': 401, 'document_id': '3549bb0ef19b0b45493f6fa077a298d7e498a7d47c352b0271adbeec33827b419c2ff5f00392c398d0f0b775f3c9c2a6be5c800bc8ccf4391c6ace06702a0595', 'entity_ids': ['2e1ad435-c02d-4601-9916-3979af75b8cb', '63e22b25-909f-461e-8892-86f537976307', '7a2fc159-cfb2-4d01-a55f-5179dfb99f05', 'cd85c9b4-0135-4865-ba8a-c7b07e007fca', '02959ad6-fb52-4d24-9fd2-53ba28239998', '125df2c4-32b4-481c-9976-65a5f76e459b', '7595fd08-940d-41e0-806d-a261f8ba46bc',