competition could drive extraordinary achievements. The Space Race between the United States and the Soviet Union provided the political motivation for Apollo, but its scientific and cultural impact transcended Cold War rivalries.\n\nThe lunar samples returned by Apollo missions revolutionized our understanding of the Moon's origin and geology. Analysis at the Lunar Receiving Laboratory at the Manned Spacecraft Center in Houston confirmed the Giant Impact Hypothesis, which proposes that the Moon formed from debris created when a Mars-sized body called Theia collided with the early Earth approximately 4.5 billion years ago.\n\nApollo also transformed our view of Earth itself. The famous Earthrise photograph taken by William Anders during Apollo 8 and the Blue Marble photograph from Apollo 17 became iconic images that helped spark the environmental movement. Seeing Earth as a fragile, beautiful sphere floating in the darkness of space gave humanity a new perspective on the planet's vulnerability.\n\nThe Artemis program, announced by NASA in 2017, aims to return humans to the Moon by the mid-2020s. Building on Apollo's legacy, Artemis plans to establish a sustainable presence on and around the Moon using the Space Launch System rocket and the Orion spacecraft. The program involves international partners including the European Space Agency, the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency, and the Canadian Space Agency.\n\nSpaceX, founded by Elon Musk, has been contracted by NASA to develop the Human Landing System for Artemis using a modified version of the Starship vehicle. Blue Origin, founded by Jeff Bezos, is developing a separate lunar lander. These commercial partnerships represent a significant evolution from the Apollo era, when the government managed virtually all aspects of spaceflight development.\n\nThe Apollo astronauts became cultural icons. Neil Armstrong, known for his humility and reluctance to seek the spotlight, was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Richard Nixon. Buzz Aldrin became a prominent advocate for Mars exploration. Many Apollo astronauts reported profound psychological and philosophical changes from seeing Earth from space, an experience known as the Overview Effect.\n", 'n_tokens': 415, 'document_id': '4f0f65796bccf7a95bdf2969da83af426406e1efb39fca53a62d5e4f5c48b7746a2e48a4045d6db39eb56b528a0b1424777d734d10e7606fef9133e399917ee8', 'entity_ids': ['2e1ad435-c02d-4601-9916-3979af75b8cb', '63e22b25-909f-461e-8892-86f537976307', 'b4d7972b-028b-4fe7-a2b6-ca88fe3a112e', 'f09acdc4-f6d4-46b5-90af-74ae1abc30ba', '95a71420-15b8-4f82-9256-107e3a726ff4', '01938521-8883-423e-b92a-e7d7f2b20292', '80401a13-083a-4cd4-91bb-cbfc0f555d6f', '8b3e510b-9736-4ca4-8350-78b9187cffc6', '55255e71-fa63-41db-8509-a045ef2d5a87', '5be12e38-364b-404e-b3a3-ddf84e582d25', '97f8a099-d464-4e3c-8b07-24bdb60c4ce4', '6440bc46-8895-4cba-986c-e76bb6a37761', 'df08fb6e-a3dd-45c4-885e-4c951029dcc5', 'a2d0c0ac-3f64-44d4-ab1c-29aaafd65295', 'e868cd1e-7059-4c77-9804-430373536c6e', '45ba592e-5b49-4ee7-9e78-79e0ce384f87', 'b4da0e29-9939-4625-b9d5-e28b27746a93', '4bc00437-0f08-4622-8787-2469ca87b29c', 'c993388a-8699-41e1-8f9a-7f7a86e7c089', '52aede1e-85fd-41bd-aff8-8a0294c3958d', 'ef98e788-7bcc-4c9d-a039-260a057d2bc6', '20c45feb-7827-4036-873d-66a59dc410d7', '394bf7e3-f282-4c81-ace4-4bc986fcc825', 'a0a9c8dc-d423-4c79-a995-83b207a16560', '935254c7-e4d2-4088-920b-774b979f1279', '21ebef9e-b734-42d5-999e-590a203dc7e2', 'bb0c2872-123f-43cd-860d-e5064910a993', '24313513-06f9-4188-893c-b4358dcf4207', '49179ac8-485b-43e3-84cd-39bad4e0564b', 'c6bb94e0-6d27-4fbc-b69b-d122e23401f5', '3ceb9fdd-918d-4af5-bb3f-fad19d9eb949', '719d0d2a-9232-43d0-873e-db40a58bfc7c', '8118033b-3677-4b30-ae0d-66e53e26c73f'], 'relationship_ids': ['a043bf02-d6fa-47de-b23b-6551acb07afc', '7cd4181b-f184-48e8-9484-614e2c6158e3', '54f7698a-2bb5-4ecd-93bc-2ccef3a71fdc', 'f2ae1686-f185-46ab-84b7-595e9466df1c', '602c7717-2958-404b-949d-c869b450bafe', '50032ecc-f173-4ec0-952f-a0a858856aad', 'b4d490d7-9540-4318-b15d-0fae08b966c3', 'd036bfb1-5a77-4180-a7f6-e0ce15756f5d', 'a59364fb-8277-4a91-a1a2-c62de691bb56', '1894633c-9c68-49b0-a5f3-275a64235372', '4f07335d-77c0-497b-ace2-c6cc6cd60c62', 'ae8f2c92-0d40-4ec4-ba3c-9cd9785394e1', '8bdb917f-5b70-44da-91b6-972402f0b610', '4829f6e6-e389-4b49-abea-810a7651b2f2', '0cc25f53-d716-4484-8c4b-c8efb5e7ce75', 'aa7d53e1-e059-48bc-879d-0dc2db2a71d7', '923ccd6a-db9a-404d-8dc1-98d8ca02f816', '48c8b55f-414b-4d89-a85d-37e7f60dd6a0', '40064121-f34c-4be0-aa4c-b44331d77b74', 'a88a59ee-be3c-4d35-99fe-a87ce4cac9dd', '21307a58-711c-43d8-a7a2-b2e44b941f80', 'e57c352a-6bd6-4d38-9b26-272e0bda22bb', '2b3b0aa8-b367-4558-af09-10d2b8e85c37', '1d1b2bbe-377c-487f-a594-6c0dff2ef933', '17d0707a-11cd-4ea3-b532-decc464a9460', 'e795ecb5-86c0-4492-b4a6-f29443555c63', 'ac080bf2-2659-4717-b96c-dc94ac5677a4', '4b6d9a1b-ae2a-43e8-8d87-2a582dba98a4', '731ad028-1142-4632-b16e-34ed0483ff45', '33c55769-45f2-487c-b925-f2416ecf701a', 'dd442803-5b0d-45a7-be90-d5a373bcb756', '9f77e008-c8c3-46b4-9aae-6507d4d98ae4', '440cf747-b4af-4292-8397-e340f66e7327', '3ea9100e-b56c-4b50-b782-fcea2e9075ee', '4747135a-ad96-470b-a15e-e6e54d18d624'], 'covariate_ids': []}, {'id': '0135e7d6044f0c25f0540cc19bd2c633d1d84904cc3aac7dd288a2ff18d759d720c0b7df603e4204942667b4b99755ee88f5dc1fd48ba164867ea6915c287536', 'human_readable_id': 3, 'text': 'The technological achievements of the Apollo program were extraordinary and required innovation across multiple engineering disciplines. The Saturn V rocket stood 363 feet tall and generated 7.5 million pounds of thrust at liftoff. It was developed at the Marshall Space Flight Center under the leadership of Wernher von Braun, a German-born rocket engineer who had previously developed the V-2 rocket during World War II.\n\nThe Command Module, built by North American Aviation in Downey, California, served as the crew quarters and flight control section for the entire mission. It was the only part of the spacecraft that returned to Earth. The Service Module, also built by North American Aviation, contained the propulsion system and most of the consumables such as oxygen, water, and electrical power.\n\nThe Lunar Module, manufactured by Grumman in Bethpage, New York, was a two-stage spacecraft designed exclusively for operations in the vacuum of space. Its descent stage included the engine for landing on the Moon and served as a launch platform for the ascent stage, which carried the crew back to lunar orbit to rendezvous with the Command Module.\n\nMission Control Center at the Manned Spacecraft Center in Houston, Texas, served as the nerve center for all Apollo missions. Flight Directors such as Gene Kranz, Chris Kraft, and Glynn Lunney coordinated thousands of engineers and controllers who monitored every aspect of the missions in real time.\n\nThe Apollo Guidance Computer, developed at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory under the direction of Charles Stark Draper, was a pioneering digital computer that used integrated circuits. Margaret Hamilton, who led the software engineering team at MIT, developed the onboard flight software that proved critical during the Apollo 11 landing when the computer successfully managed multiple program alarms.\n\nThe program also drove advances in materials science, telecommunications, life support systems, and project management. Many technologies developed for Apollo found applications in everyday life, from water purification systems to fireproof materials. The total cost of the Apollo program was approximately 25.4 billion dollars, equivalent to over 150 billion dollars in modern currency.\n', 'n_tokens': 411, 'document_id': '0135e7d6044f0c25f0540cc19bd2c633d1d84904cc3aac7dd288a2ff18d759d720c0b7df603e4204942667b4b99755ee88f5dc1fd48ba164867ea6915c287536', 'entity_ids': ['2e1ad435-c02d-4601-9916-3979af75b8cb', '383d206e-5328-4531-9709-c173161eb12b', 'b155f528-dfa9-46e0-8037-2c8df4773d8a', 'f9ef2cc8-fad2-4d8f-a929-a45b434f02d5', 'cd85c9b4-0135-4865-ba8a-c7b07